    16	---
    17	
    18	## 2. SEVERITY DEFINITIONS
    19	
    20	| Level | Meaning | Handling |
    21	| --- | --- | --- |
    22	| P0 | Blocker: exploitable security issue, auth bypass, destructive data loss | Block merge |
    23	| P1 | Required: correctness bug, spec mismatch, must-fix gate issue | Fix before merge |
    24	| P2 | Suggestion: non-blocking improvement, documentation polish, style or maintainability follow-up | Optional or schedule follow-up |
    25	
    26	Escalation rule: if confidence is low but impact is high, classify toward the higher severity and state the uncertainty explicitly.
    27	
    28	---
    29	
    30	## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
     1	---
     2	title: Review UX - Single Pass
     3	description: Interactive single-pass review behavior for human-facing review sessions.
     4	---
     5	
     6	# Review UX - Single Pass
     7	
     8	Interactive behavior for a one-pass review where findings are reported first and the human chooses what happens next.
     9	
    10	---
    11	
    12	## 1. OVERVIEW
    13	
    14	Interactive single-pass review behavior for human-facing review sessions.
    15	
    16	---
    17	
    18	## 2. HUMAN INTERACTION BEHAVIOR
    19	
    20	- Review first, implement second.
    21	- After publishing findings, ask the user what to do next before writing code.
    22	- Keep the prompt concrete and mode-aware; do not ask open-ended process questions unless scope is unclear.
    23	- If no blocking findings exist, still offer explicit next-step choices instead of assuming implementation work.
    24	
    25	Recommended next-step options:
    26	
    27	1. Fix all findings
    28	2. Fix `P0` and `P1` only
    29	3. Fix selected findings
    30	4. No implementation changes
    31	
    32	---
    33	
    34	## 3. REPORT FLOW
    35	
    36	Use this flow for interactive review responses:
    37	
    38	1. State what was reviewed and the scope source (`git diff`, staged diff, file list, or commit range).
    39	2. Publish findings ordered by severity.
    40	3. Summarize merge posture or risk level briefly.
    41	4. Ask the user what to do next.
    42	
    43	If no diff is present, report:
    44	
    45	- What was checked
    46	- That no diff was found
    47	- A concrete follow-up choice: staged changes only, specific commit/range, or selected files
    48	
    49	---
    50	
    51	## 4. MODE-SPECIFIC PRESENTATION
    52	
    53	Choose the lightest presentation that fits the request:
    54	
    55	- Findings-only: list the issues with evidence and stop after the next-step prompt.
    56	- Findings + gate recommendation: include `APPROVE`, `REQUEST_CHANGES`, or `COMMENT` after the findings.
    57	- Findings + fix follow-up options: present the review, then offer concrete remediation choices without starting implementation automatically.
    58	
    59	Presentation rules:
    60	
    61	- Keep findings ahead of summary sections.
    62	- Use plain-language impact statements.
    63	- Distinguish optional advice clearly from required fixes.
    64	- Acknowledge notable strengths briefly after the required findings, not before them.
    65	
    66	---
    67	
    68	## 5. PR AND PRE-COMMIT GUIDANCE
    69	
    70	For PR review:
    71	
    72	- Check for scope drift and call out unrelated changes that should be split.
    73	- Assess contract and backward-compatibility risk for externally visible changes.
    74	- Tie the overall recommendation to merge readiness.
    75	
    76	For pre-commit or staged review:
    77	
    78	- Focus on the staged diff or requested file set.
    79	- Prioritize the fastest blocking feedback first.
    80	- Keep remediation suggestions small and easy to apply before commit.
    81	
    82	---
    83	
    84	## 6. RELATED RESOURCES
    85	
    86	- [review_core.md](./review_core.md) - Shared doctrine used by both interactive and deep review modes.
    87	- [quick_reference.md](./quick_reference.md) - Lightweight index for the review reference set.
    88	- [test_quality_checklist.md](./test_quality_checklist.md) - Test quality and coverage checks for changed tests.
    89	
    90	---
    91	
